Date: 21 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

Statistical graphics can be found at:
<http://www.hjones-sons.co.uk/graph.htm>
Today's [21 Apr 2001 total is given as 20 [new cases. Interpolation
of this graph and the number at the end of the series, gives a rerun
of the article by Roly Tinline and Martin Hugh-Jones, who reported an
8-day interfarm interval during 1967-68. J Hygiene (1976) 77: 141-153,
"Studies on the 1967-68 foot and mouth disease epidemic: incubation
period and herd serial interval." Towards the end of that epidemic it
stretched to "about two weeks."
Deja vu all over again. If this is continues to hold true, we can
expect to see an up-and-down progress to the end, with accompanying
increases and losses of confidence. - MHJ.
******
[3
Date: 21 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily Telegraph, London 21 Apr 2001 [edited
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk:80/et?ac=002559874442765&rtmo=gjSfkfru&atm
o=tttttttd&pg=/et/01/4/21/nfnm121.html>

Britain will not be allowed to trade its meat or livestock with the
rest of the world for at least 3 years, twice previous official
estimates, one of the Government's principal scientific advisers on
foot and mouth disease (FMD) said. Gareth Davies, a former head of
epidemiology at MAFF and the European Commission, said the delay would
be largely the same regardless of whether or not the Government
decided on selective vaccination to bring down the number of livestock
that had to be killed. [Presumably this means killed immediately.
Earlier statements have been that all vaccinated livestock would
eventually have to be killed in order for the UK to regain FMD-free
status. - Mod.JW
Mr Davies, who presided over Europe's switch of policy from
vaccination to slaughter, said he had changed his mind and there now
had to be "a complete rethink" of how the European Union fought animal
diseases. He and the Government's other scientific advisers favor the
limited use of vaccination.
Conditions on farms had changed with huge numbers of animals
concentrated on single farms and thousands of livestock movements
every week by road. Mr Davies was recently drafted on to the chief
scientist's panel, which advises the crisis committee chaired by Tony
Blair.
Previously, the Government's line has been that Britain's
"disease-free" status could be restored a year after the last
vaccinated animal was killed or a year after the last case of the
disease, whichever was the longer. However, it is difficult to remove
a block from a country.
If the last case takes place towards the end of the year, farmers have
been assuming trade would open up in approximately 18 months. Mr
Davies, now a consultant to the EU and the United Nations (UN) Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO), said: "It is important to realize
in this epidemic it's going to take us several years before we are
able to prove to our trading partners that we are free of disease. I
would have thought we are talking about 3 years. We have to prove we
have no circulating infection in the livestock population. That means
an extensive program of serological surveillance, and following up
with other examinations, to prove to our trading partners we are free
of circulating antibodies."
A number of "false positives" and true cases could be expected well
after the last declared case -- which vets assume could be towards the
end of this year because of the notorious "long tail" of FMD
epidemics. Under EU rules it is theoretically possible for a region
not having the disease to regain its disease-free status within 3
months of the last case in the country as a whole.
But Mr Davies said if he was sitting in Brussels he would "find it
difficult to conceive of realistic regionalization at the moment." He
said MAFF scientists were already looking at an "exit strategy for
clearing the national sheep flocks -- the principal carrier of the
disease in this outbreak -- so we can say we do not have disease".
