[6
Date: 19 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Associated Press 19 Apr 2001 [edited

MEIGH, Northern Ireland -- This borderland has long been known a haven
for smugglers. These days, the most dangerous contraband is
[livestock. On both sides of the frontier dividing the Republic of
Ireland from Northern Ireland, livestock smuggling has become the bete
noire of authorities fighting to contain the spread of foot-and-mouth
disease (FMD).
Unauthorized movement of a herd of sheep is being blamed for Northern
Ireland's first outbreak of the highly contagious virus 6 weeks ago,
in the border village of Meigh. Illicit animal transport is also being
investigated as a factor in 2 new cases having appeared 6 days ago in
the province. A third suspect farm has been sealed off.
Since smuggling has continued since the first outbreak, there is [no
question as to the smugglers' motive. The incentive is money.
Livestock smugglers profit by the strength of the British pound versus
the euro, the European currency to which the Irish pound is linked.
They also gain by illegally claiming European Union farming subsidies
available in the Republic of Ireland, but not in the north. The heart
of the smuggling trade is South Armagh, a traditional stronghold of
the Irish Republican Army. Although the IRA has been observing a
cease-fire since 1997, some of its senior members are known to have
turned their hand to smuggling rackets that traffic in fuel and
cigarettes.
All livestock movement is now banned in Northern Ireland, so
authorities are struggling with the twin tasks of halting cross-border
trafficking and preventing animals from being moved clandestinely
within the province.
FMD usually spells economic disaster for farmers in countries
exporting agricultural products. Another problem is tracking animals
possibly brought into Northern Ireland on condition they be
slaughtered immediately, but being kept alive and resold instead.
Authorities are now trying to trace the movements of cows, sheep, and
pigs imported in the weeks before the disease surfaced in England.
